poem:
The Sciencefair Wight

Twas labblig at the fairgrounds, and the glintly projects hummed,
The fizzlenoggers fumbled, and the whifflesticks were plumbed;
Beware the Sparkwick, my child! the Glowerproof! the Judge-snarl grim!
Hold fast thy flibberflask and wit, and mind thy bright-eyed prim.

He took his solder-sword in hand; long time the gizmo-glow he eyed —
And stood awhile by poster-board where tiny theories bide;
And as the ticking tomes did tick and test-tubes glorp and sing,
Came wobble-wires and bumbling blots that tried to steal his spring.

One, two! One, two! And through they flew, the fizz and foobar throng;
He switched the flux and tuned the hum, he spoke his data song;
The Sparkwhiff hissed, the Volt-gnash snapped — but lo! his circuit true,
Unfurled the light, the model sang, the judges hummed, “A clue!”

O Callooh! Callay! they cried — Hoorah! the ribbon bright he bore;
Back through the whirligiggy lanes he tramped to home's warm door;
So heed, young chums, before you go: prepare thy plots and proofs,
And brave the fair with curious heart — return with tinkered truths.

Déjà Vu in the Gloamwyrm's Lair

In gloam-scarft hours, memory-springs ping and sing;
Déjà vu taps quiet-tongued at the brain's pale rim.
Therimble the Gloamwyrm lounges on the time-thin sill,
Quippity-quirks drip from his maw, a pearly still.

He hums in coinages: flossle, brummock, zindle-glow;
"We’ve walked this room before," he whispers slow.
The floor folds twice, a mirrorwing loop of old,
While time-twigs twist and thrums of silver cold.

A moment loops—snick-snack of fate in a lacey knot;
The mint of memory jingles, and I am not forgot.
We pass the door we passed a dozen times before;
And at the threshold breathe the same thin thyme and roar.

So flibble-wonder, mind-drift lullaby, here;
Therimble nods: déjà vu is a curious gear.
Meet me at the quibble-crest where lanes align;
And call this moment home with a glint of sign.

Wingsward Whimsy: A Backstage Ballad

’Twas gloaming in the wings, where velvet hush did sigh;
lamp-moths fluttered, and shadow-breaths drifted by.
Quillow the Wingweaver, nimble-sprite with twill-tale tail,
stitch-snug the hush to heartbeat, weaving dusk with whim and wail.
With plink-plonk of backstage lamps, the rail-slats softly flip;
the curtainlace rustles, counting heartbeats on the lip.
Wing-sashes creak a lattice-song of squeak and whirl;
while velvet veils flutter, letting night-wind swirl.
Quillow croons a gobble-gum that curls the air in twine;
bead-sparkles wink along the hem of sleepy shine.
The proscenium sighs with fringe of glitter and gleam;
the wing-angel nods, and listening crowds softly dream.
Spinthrift breezes tip the seam, with hush-echo snicker-snack;
fastenings tug-twist in time with every careful knack.
Thus knits the stage to life again, when rumor-singers say;
the wings unfold their secret kiss, and light steals into day.
Quillow winks, "The show begins where shadows begin;"
and slips behind the velvet veil, letting the magic in.

The Slithy Science Fair

'Twas slithy morning at the science fair, the benches hummed with glassy light;
Beakers blinked like moonlit boats, and gadgets whirred bright as kinetic night;
Glimmergadgetry whispered through the aisles in quarkle-words alight;
Curious minds spoke fizz-wink phrases, merry as a starry sprite.

Admonition: prepare thy kit, calibrate the spark before the rite;
Label thy jars, test every wire, and map thy talk in careful light;
Practice thy patter till it rhymes with rhythm and data glitters bright;
For haste will twist the tale and dim thy wonder’s shining might.

Then booths unfold with whirr and whirl of clever contraptions grand;
A wind-wisp engine, fizzing clocks, and drones that glitter on demand;
The crowd claps soft and then erupts as dreams take crisp, brave flight;
Each student beams—a little star—across the gadget-laden land.

When judges crown the bravest minds, we whirl in a jubilant tilt;
Prizes chime like silver bells as clever hearts glow with nimble wit;
Homeward through the moonlit park we stroll, our pockets full of grit;
Back to beds at last, with tomorrow’s sparks and songs to knit.

Déjà Vu in the Grindlewock's Gleam

'Twas déjà vu in a gloam-warped glade,
Where Grindlewock gribbered through memory's braid;
Its moon-eyed grin lit the seen-back anew,
And time pawed the floor with a familiar shoe.

I whispered flimworp to the sighing air;
Quexle-bloom drifted from the mossy lair;
The trees muttered slithy doodads of lore,
While déjà vu opened a door to the old floor.

The Grindlewock bowed, whisker-tipped and wry;
A second self rose, my yesterday’s sky;
We shared a chuff of brume and a laugh of hue;
Then time winked shut, and brought me back to you.

Wingwhisper and the Velvetrath

Murkling was the velvet air; the flats did shivel-shoon,
The rope-rigs hummed and sandbags swayed beneath a ghostish moon;
The gelglows leaked in colorflakes; the cuewind held its breath,
And hushle-crews in blackbird blacks skulked side of painted death.

“Beware the Velvetrath, my sprout, that prowls the leftmost seam!
Its tassel-teeth and shadow-sheen will snag a player’s dream.
Beware the Gripling’s clatter-gnaw; shun gaffer-tar and glue!”
Thus spoke the Stagey Sage to me by proscenoon’s dim blue.

I sought my propblade, silver-foam—my tapeless, true brigleam;
I donned my hushboots, sleek with quiet, slid through split-seam;
Through Wingwhisper I tip-to-tore, where dropcloths drape and dive,
Where cue-birds chirr in headset shells and spike-marks wake alive.

The wingwoods creaked with flats and trees, all painted leaf and bark,
The scrimlet fogged with moonish dust; the flyloft loomed and stark;
The line-set ladders whickered low, the sandbags dozed in rows,
And somewhere deep a bow-clamp sang, soft surrepto-nose.

And, lo! the Velvetrath slid forth, all tassel-tail and fringe;
Its velvet-maw went swuff and swall; its whiskers sang a hinge;
Its eyes were lamps of limelight-lurk; its breath a curtain-sigh;
It lapped the silence twice or thrice and draftered, creeping nigh.

I raised my brigleam, wrote it wide—a figure-eight of glare;
It crumple-cracked the hushful dark and parted gaffer air;
The Velvetrath made swarfy leaps; it flurched with muffled feet;
We grappled mid the canvas-storm, in strobe of cue and beat.

I flicked a cue upon my belt; the boardling blinked a bloom,
A blackout fell like velvet rain and ate the wingish gloom;
The Velvetrath gave one soft yawp, then settled, tame and slight,
It dozed into an ottoman—a cushion made of night.

I bore it—fold by folded fold—toward proscenium’s glow;
The Stagey Sage in promptbook cloak gave nods of yesso-know:
“O footlamp-joy! O cue-complete! You tamed the tassel-wraith!
Now strike the fear and set the scene; we open, close to faith.”

Murkling stays the velvet air; the flats go shivel-shoon,
The gelglows braid their colorflakes around the make-belune;
And somewhere in the wings it purrs, my ottovelted friend—
The Velvetrath of Wingwhisper, the hush that helps pretend.

Awlward and the Borewyrm

In gloamish shop, the threadlings looped; the thimbles thrumble-throd,
The leather dreamed in pucker-dunes; the tacklets clinked and clod;
On oaken bench with gleamish grin and tip so keenly small,
Sat prickle-proud and pierce-perturb, the ever-seeking Awl.

The Borewyrm burrowed buckram-bad through belt and boot and pack;
It left the holes all widdershin and turned the laces slack;
Its mouth was like a grommet-press, its tail a twisty spool;
It loathed the straight of stitchwright ways; it mocked the maker’s rule.

Then Awlward slipped from peg on peg, a spry bright-hafted sprite;
He wore a shoelace baldric thin and winked with tinsel light;
His hornish haft, his prickle-point—so braveling, lean, and tall—
He chirped in little piercer-cant: I pierce, I guide, I awl.

The Borewyrm sloughed the cutting board with burble, glue, and grit;
It slither-scurfed the bench’s edge and sniffed the cobbler’s kit;
Awlward danced in prickle-steps, a twizzle-tilting brawl—
Skritch-skreel! he stitched a silver road of holes both straight and small.

Through that true trace the laces flew, like quickling serpents tamed;
They looped and cinched and clevered tight; the bore-beast found it shamed;
It gnawed the knots; its gnashings stalled; its wobble-wriggles fall;
For every chomp met stitchbound strength by Awlward, brave and small.

With whorl and twine the creature drooped, in lasslet loops confined;
It sighed a button-bogglesigh and left its borings blind;
Awlward pressed the final prick; the shop returned to lull;
And threadlings sang in cobbler-speech: Awl’s well—the work is full.
